= Important Principles related to taking means (Asbāb)

1. When a person takes means, their reliance must be on Allāh not on the means
   themselves because Allāh is the one who creates and enables means.

2. One must understand that these means are tied to Allāh’s decree and will
   (Qadar).

3. There are two ways to establish valid means:

*First:* Through Islamic legislation (Sharʿ). Example: Honey is a means of
healing.

Evidence: Allāh's saying,

#quran-block[
  ثُمَّ كُلِي مِن كُلِّ ٱلثَّمَرَٰتِ فَٱسۡلُكِي سُبُلَ رَبِّكِ ذُلُلٗاۚ يَخۡرُجُ
  مِنۢ بُطُونِهَا شَرَابٞ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ أَلۡوَٰنُهُۥ فِيهِ شِفَآءٞ لِّلنَّاسِۚ
  إِنَّ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَأٓيَةٗ لِّقَوۡمٖ يَتَفَكَّرُونَ ٦٩
][
  Then eat from all the fruits and follow the ways of your Lord laid down [for
  you]." There emerges from their bellies a drink, varying in colors, in which
  there is healing for people. Indeed in that is a sign for a people who give
  thought (Al-Naḥl Q16:69)
]

#sc[Second:] Through experience and natural law (Qadar).

Example: Fire is a means of burning.

However, for something to be accepted through experience, its effect must be
clearly evident after direct contact, because unclear effects might be based on
claims or illusions

For example: The claim that wearing a ring protects from the evil eye—this is a
false or imagined cause.